Next, let us divide both sides by the -\$1.40 to cancel out the coefficient of RN. This is computed as follows: 
$$\begin{aligned}
\dfrac{\text{ -\$1.40RN}}{\text{-1.40}}&=\dfrac{\text{ -\$13.60}}{\text{-1.40 }}\\[10pt]
{\text{RN}}&={\textbf{9.71}}
\end{aligned}$$ 

**The number of rights required to buy stocks is 9.71 rights.**

Finally, we can now compute the shares that the company is have before the offering was made. This is computed by multiplying the number of rights required which we have computed in step 8 and the total number of new shares from step 4. This is computed as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}
{\text{Old shares}}&={\text{Rights needed $\times$ New shares }}\\
&={\text{9.71  $\times$ 485,294 }}\\
&={\text{4,712,205 shares}}
\end{aligned}$$
